PCI 2095 - Move Oakdale servers to Shoreview
column12:
Description of Idea:
LSPA engineering is now 90% at 707. Opening Solidworks files are large and takes a while to open. For Instance opening a particular file for me in Oakdale it takes 7minutes and 45 seconds, 707 is takes 15 minutes and 35 seconds and at home over VPN it takes 60 minutes 45 seconds. For all instances was hardwired to the internet.

Servers are located in Oakdale that is why it is faster there. Shoreview you still need to pull the files from Oakdale and I don't know what what the connection is between there but it takes about double the time to open. At home the VPN is around 40 Mbps, but when opening cad files it goes down to 2Mbps. I don't know why this happens, it maybe using upload speed or talking back to the servers. PaR is on EPDM so after opening the files for the first time you get a local copy and don't have to re-download files, so opening large files this isn't as big as an issue. For LSPA working in windows folders files need to be downloaded each time. This is probably why most of the LSPA ME's came back into the office over the PaR because working offsite with Solidworks is hard to open files efficiently.

Solutions:
Move LSPA CAD servers to 707, to increase the speed where 90% of the engineers are located.
Increase VPN download speed for CAD files.
Move LSPA project into EPDM - I know this coming but a ways out.
Benefit from Idea:
Opening Solidworks files is done daily and depending on the files size this can add up to a lot of saved time saved for files to open.

Step: Not Used
Prev. Notes: Comment: We are already moving servers from Oakdale to Shoreview in preparation for the shutdown of the site. Completion isn't feasible prior to actual closure of the facility.. Record Status: Not Used.

column5: PCI 2171 - Changes to Daily Project Activity Report
column12:
Description of Idea:

Add "Upcoming Actions" and "Overdue Actions" to the "Daily Project Activity Report" email organized by due date.

Benefit from Idea:

Projects have actions that can be assigned to different resources as an easy way to create and manage tasks on a project. Including a list of open actions to everyone's daily activity email would allow those actions to be clearly seen and tracked by the assigned party. Currently many actions are forgotten about because there is not an automatic reminder to complete upcoming or overdue actions. This will allow actions to be completed faster and create greater accountability to execute quickly.

Description of Idea:

Under each project's home page, there is an "actions" tab. The actions that are created are organized in a seemingly random order that changes as time progresses and more actions are added. This makes it hard to find a specific task as their position in the list changes frequently. The usefulness of the actions tab would be drastically improved by having a permanent order for the actions.

It is proposed that another column is added that has an action number. By default, the actions tab would be sorted by action number. This would stabilize the order of the actions.

Benefit from Idea:

If this idea was implemented, the actions tab would become even more useful. This leads to wider adoption. Having action items in an easily accessible location enables the project team to collaborate effectively which allows projects to be executed with velocity.

Benefit from Idea:

Reduce cost of unused software licenses. Ensure correct coverage for licensing. Streamline the renewal process. Provide accurate cost metrics for reporting and future budgeting

However when you do the same thing for a SP job this column does not refresh as you enter in the new dates.
 
Thank you!

Description of Idea:
An App similar to the NCR app that Mfg Engineering can use to notify Planning that work orders are now available in a Planned state. Planners would have sign-offs on the app to ensure that scrubbing, APR, MRP and scheduling was completed. Once all items were completed then it would notify Purchasing/Purchasing supervisor that the items are available to purchase
Benefit from Idea:
There isn't currently a report that shows all of the work orders in a planned state and therefore it is difficult to see what hasn't been released into production. Also APR is a manual process and due to the potential length of time between long lead work orders and RFM of assemblies this would help eliminate not running APR and duplicate buying of those long lead items.

column5: PCI 2262 - PNM changes to commodity codes
column12:
http://parapps/PCI/PCIdetail.cfm?PCI=2262

Description of Idea:
In part number master, there is currently a drop down for commodity codes where you can select what an item represents. I was told by Alex Cunov that the commodity codes are directly linked to project requirements by quality and Marine owns them all. I am not sure if this helps purchasing know what shop to use or what the function is.

However, my idea is to either use this commodity code drop down or a different drop down menu in part number master for the part number that allows engineers to select an option that basically gives a pool of vendors for purchasing to choose from. Then the part number master page shows material, finish, and a pool of shops to choose from.

Benefit from Idea:
Since engineers are no longer quoting parts, this helps ensure that we can show purchasing at least what vendors we would choose from. Since all this information would be on part number master, they would not even have to open up the drawing because engineering directed their pool of vendors to choose from. I still believe that the engineers should be quoting parts, but this option will give the engineers still some control and allow purchasing to do their jobs more efficiently.

column5: PCI 2326 - Field service additions to Labor Utilization report

column12:
http://parapps/PCI/PCIdetail.cfm?PCI=2278

Description of Idea:
Add a way for engineers to view current status and queue of EPDM PDF creation tasks. When creating drawing PDFs for MA/ECO transitions as well as manual PDF creation, sometimes it isn’t clear whether the system is working or when a user can expect a PDF to be created. This could be due to:
• The file being large, and it will take a long time to generate the PDF. If the file hasn’t generated after a period of time, the user may not know if the task is being processed, and may try to generate the PDF again, bogging down the system for all users because the same long task will appear multiple times in the queue.
• Many PDFs trying to be generated at the same time. There is no way to know whether the system is working through a long queue or isn’t working, especially if it is a small file that the user would expect to be generated quickly.
It would be helpful to be able to see the current queue of PDF tasks and to be able to display some kind of available status information about the current in-progress task (start timestamp, process step, other).

Benefit from Idea:
Allow for faster PDF generation times by avoiding large duplicate tasks, allow for planning of work around task machine bandwidth, be able to see if a critical system is functioning properly and avoid unnecessary escalation if it is.

PCI 2246 - Changes to Solidworks PAR Custom Properties macro
column12:
http://parapps/PCI/PCIdetail.cfm?PCI=2246

Description of Idea:
When running the PAR Custom Properties macro to pull data from PAR part number master into SolidWorks, a pop up appears after one hits "Apply" to let one know that everything went well. However, this is just one more pop up one must click through when populating part properties. While this consumes a small amount of time, that time adds up over all of the mechanical designers over a year. In order to save time, this pop up should be eliminated. A pop up should only appear if something went wrong. Otherwise, the macro should close without requiring more clicks to acknowledge that things went well.

Benefit from Idea:
If implemented, this idea will save the engineering department time, and time is money in business.

column12:
The IS dept and the Solidworks CAD administrator should have metrics for Solidworks crashes and should strive to reduce the number of crashes. The metrics should include at a minimum:
    Individual crashes. I currently crash about twice a day so I should get more attention than someone that crashes once a month. Crashes may be caused by individual computer setups. Crashes may be caused by corrupt model files. This metric may reduce those crashes.
    Average crashes by physical location. Some crashes are caused by network issues. A metric by location may highlight these.
    There are surely more metrics than these to improve the reliability of Solidworks.

Description of Idea:
Improve the Jobscope BOM tool by combining the "Item #" field and the "Engineering #" field into one category. These items are never different from each other and very easy to miss one or the other. If missed, it makes life difficult for Mike until the engineer goes back in and fixes the issue.

Benefit from Idea:
Prevents simple errors of missing one of the fields or having differing numbers in each. This will also prevent slowing up Mike when we are trying to release. Less hours spent fixing these small mistakes means more money saved.
